WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:01.700
Good morning, everyone. I'm Bill Sellers.

2
00:00:01.840 --> 00:00:05.560
Welcome to the session on new advances in bispecific antibody

3
00:00:05.620 --> 00:00:09.260
development. It's my pleasure to chair this session.

4
00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:12.500
Can I get the first slide?

5
00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:18.020
That's the next one.

6
00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:27.940
Okay, so just to start with my disclosures, these are my

7
00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:31.880
disclosures, but one in particular is relevant for today, which is Red Ridge Bio.

8
00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:35.900
It's a company working on biparotopic antibodies, and the topic

9
00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:39.540
I will discuss is highly relevant to that startup company.

10
00:00:40.100 --> 00:00:43.120
So first, for today's session, it's my pleasure to welcome Dr.

11
00:00:43.340 --> 00:00:46.760
Nina Weiser, who's now an executive director of

12
00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:50.280
multispecific antibody therapeutics at Designworks, and Dr.

13
00:00:50.380 --> 00:00:53.580
John Desjarlais, the chief science officer at Zencor.

14
00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:57.980
And I can promise you they will know way more about the way

15
00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:00.000
to engineer antibodies than I will.

16
00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:03.320
So I'll give you the academic view or attempts at

17
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.960
making bispecific or biparotopic antibodies.

18
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.860
So my first experience in this started when I

19
00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:12.760
was at Novartis, and

20
00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:17.140
we were trying to make antibodies against the LRP6

21
00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:17.700
receptor.

22
00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:22.240
And the LRP6 receptor has a series of propeller domains which bind

23
00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:25.980
distinct WNT ligands through different propeller domains.

24
00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:30.280
And what we found is if we made an antibody to the

25
00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:34.160
first propeller, we could block WNT1 binding and WNT1

26
00:01:34.300 --> 00:01:38.160
signaling, but it actually became an agonist in the presence of

27
00:01:38.200 --> 00:01:41.820
WNT3. And if we made a WNT3

28
00:01:41.980 --> 00:01:45.360
blocking antibody, shown here, blocking WNT3-dependent

29
00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:49.020
activation, it became an agonist in the setting of

30
00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:49.720
WNT1.

31
00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:51.460
So

32
00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:56.020
an antibody was assembled, the format of which is shown here, which blocked both

33
00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:00.220
of the propellers, the WNT1 propeller and the WNT3 propeller.

34
00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:03.760
And these otherwise agonistic antibodies became pure

35
00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:07.320
antagonists of either WNT1 or WNT3-dependent

36
00:02:08.021 --> 00:02:08.400
signaling.

37
00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:13.260
So that just says something about the importance of knowing the epitopes and being

38
00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:17.049
able to block multiple epitopes, in this case, to create true

39
00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:20.300
antagonistic antibodies.

40
00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:25.120
So just so we're all on the same page, what is a biparotopic

41
00:02:25.180 --> 00:02:28.720
antibody? It's a subclass of bispecific antibodies,

42
00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:32.420
which instead of recognizing the same antigen,

43
00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:37.150
which is the case for a bivalent monoparotopic antibody,

44
00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:40.870
instead, it recognizes two different antigens on the same

45
00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:44.600
protein. And the way we went about making such biparotopic

46
00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:48.300
antibodies is to take parental monovalent

47
00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:51.980
antibodies and introduce mutations that allow

48
00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:53.120
for the

49
00:02:54.020 --> 00:02:57.310
assembly of paired heavy and light chains,

50
00:02:57.400 --> 00:03:01.280
recognizing the epitopes into a chimeric biparotopic

51
00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:01.860
antibody.

52
00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:06.810
So when I left Novartis and came back to academia, I was very interested in how

53
00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:10.640
extensive biparotopic antibodies could be and how differentiated their

54
00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:14.260
pharmacology might be from standard bivalent antibodies.

55
00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:17.720
And so I thought, what would be a really good test case?

56
00:03:17.900 --> 00:03:21.000
What would be a hard test case, not an easy test case?

57
00:03:21.490 --> 00:03:24.680
And I was drawn to the presence of

58
00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:28.040
FGFR2 fusion proteins in a number of cancers, but in

59
00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:31.850
particular in intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma, where

60
00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:35.590
the fusions are all on the C-terminus on the intracellular side.

61
00:03:35.990 --> 00:03:39.590
And these fusions, first described by Arul Chinnaiyan, are thought to

62
00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:43.690
activate the receptor by constitutive dimerization.

63
00:03:44.100 --> 00:03:47.910
Yet interestingly, the extracellular domain for all of these is

64
00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:51.350
maintained, shown here. So one question I had was,

65
00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:55.780
well, could we make an antibody that would be potent enough to

66
00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:59.240
degrade or to block the activity of a

67
00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:03.320
receptor in which the dimerization is being induced by an intracellular

68
00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:07.340
fusion event? And I thought if we could do that, that would be really something

69
00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:08.160
special.

70
00:04:09.340 --> 00:04:12.940
So we started by going to the patent literature and pulling six different

71
00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:17.079
FGFR2 antibodies, and by reading the patents, we roughly thought we could

72
00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:20.380
assign different epitope bins to the different binders.

73
00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:24.400
So six different antibodies mapped to the FGFR2 extracellular

74
00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:28.360
domain, as shown here. And then we took those parental antibodies and just

75
00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:31.320
reproduced or tried to reproduce their

76
00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:33.860
blocking ability. So

77
00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:38.380
we created BaF3 cells that are driven by the fusion FGFR2

78
00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:40.630
protein. And you can see when we add

79
00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:45.180
fibroblast growth factor, we can block

80
00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:48.980
FGF-dependent growth with four of these

81
00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:52.820
antibodies shown here, while two antibodies which are not in the ligand binding

82
00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:55.780
domain have no activity. Just for reference,

83
00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.940
antibody E is bemratezumab, which is a clinically relevant

84
00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:05.020
FGFR2 antibody. However, if we took those same BaF3 cells, which

85
00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:08.580
are dependent on this fusion protein for growth and don't really need the

86
00:05:08.620 --> 00:05:11.540
ligand to grow, and now we add the antibody,

87
00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:16.320
you can see several of the antibodies become agonists in the absence

88
00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:20.280
of ligand, including antibody A and C, and others just lose

89
00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:22.660
their inhibitory activity in general.

90
00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:26.100
So while they're great at blocking ligand-dependent signaling, they don't do

91
00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:30.090
anything to the tonic signaling except for one antibody,

92
00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:33.500
which in a dose-independent manner, had some ability to

93
00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:37.520
block growth of these FGFR2-driven BaF3 cells in the

94
00:05:37.580 --> 00:05:41.440
absence of ligand. So with these six antibodies, we then used

95
00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:45.460
that duo-body approach I showed you before to make all possible

96
00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:49.620
pairwise combinations, including remaking the parental

97
00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:53.440
antibodies indicated by B. And if you do the math, if you have a six

98
00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:57.330
by six grid, that creates 15 unique biparotopic

99
00:05:57.420 --> 00:06:01.260
antibodies and six reconstituted parental antibodies.

100
00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:05.040
And then we profiled these in a number of assays.

101
00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:08.380
SoFirst, using MSD Set, which is a solution

102
00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:09.900
binding assay,

103
00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:12.620
we measured the affinity of these antibodies.

104
00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:16.200
And you can see, compared to the parental antibodies, almost all the

105
00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:19.660
biparatopics gain significant affinity or

106
00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:23.310
avidity, though in solution, this is really not true

107
00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:26.530
avidity because the two antigens are floating around.

108
00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:30.380
So to try to get an idea of true avidity, we used

109
00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:33.690
acoustic force spectroscopy, where beads coated with

110
00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:37.540
antibodies were displaced by sound from cells bearing

111
00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:41.620
FGFR2 fusion proteins, so we could measure the force required

112
00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:45.490
to displace the antibody-coated bead from an actual

113
00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:49.260
cell surface expressing FGFR2. And you can see two

114
00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:53.240
antibodies, BC and BD, both had the highest

115
00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:56.760
affinity in solution binding and the highest avidity in the

116
00:06:56.800 --> 00:07:00.320
acoustic force spectroscopy, and these were significantly

117
00:07:00.360 --> 00:07:02.740
improved over the parental antibodies.

118
00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:08.480
So these antibodies, along with their parental precursors, B,

119
00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:12.280
D, and C, were then tested for blocking colony

120
00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:13.760
formation or growth

121
00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:18.460
of the FGFR2 fusions. And you can see in colony

122
00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:22.500
formation assays, compared to the parental antibodies, BD and

123
00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:26.200
BC had significant ability to block

124
00:07:26.260 --> 00:07:30.200
colony formation, which is just quantified here on the

125
00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:32.300
right in a dose-dependent fashion.

126
00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:37.320
So working with Nabil Bardeesy's lab, we then took a

127
00:07:37.520 --> 00:07:39.440
patient-derived line that he created.

128
00:07:39.470 --> 00:07:43.160
It's now a stable line from intrahepatic

129
00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:46.400
cholangiocarcinoma patient that is driven by the

130
00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:50.180
FGFR2-OPTN fusion, and we compared the

131
00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:54.020
activity of, in this case, the naked antibodies in blocking

132
00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:58.240
tumor growth shown here. And you can see antibodies BD and

133
00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:02.160
BC had significant inhibition of tumor growth, though

134
00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:05.440
not regression, compared to the parental antibodies.

135
00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:08.750
By comparison, if this model were to be treated with

136
00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:12.380
the relay FGFR2 selective small

137
00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:16.420
molecule inhibitor, we would see minus 20% tumor regression.

138
00:08:16.520 --> 00:08:20.460
So it's not as good as the small molecule, but it's also not so far off.

139
00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:25.150
Interestingly, when we harvested the tumors at the end of the

140
00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:27.940
in vivo experiment, you can see

141
00:08:28.820 --> 00:08:32.461
the striking absence of FGFR2 on the surface.

142
00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:36.640
And we had previously shown that we were unable to disrupt the

143
00:08:36.660 --> 00:08:40.280
dimers, which were our original hypothesis that we would be blocking the

144
00:08:40.300 --> 00:08:44.220
dimers. But now we see instead that we're down-regulating

145
00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:48.030
the receptor. So to further pursue this, we then looked at

146
00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:51.010
internalization using a Fab Fluor

147
00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:55.220
binder that binds to an antibody, and then when internalized into the

148
00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:59.160
lysosome and the pH is acidic, turns red.

149
00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:03.500
And so you can see here that antibodies BD and BC compared to

150
00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:07.180
the parentals BC and D have markedly improved

151
00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:11.200
internalization. And this is lysosome-dependent, as we can block

152
00:09:11.240 --> 00:09:15.020
this downregulation of FGFR2 by treatment with the lysosomal

153
00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:17.420
inhibitor bafilomycin A1.

154
00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:22.940
So that suggested that our activity was

155
00:09:22.980 --> 00:09:26.340
primarily driven by loss of FGFR2 through

156
00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:29.810
internalization and degradation in a lysosomal-dependent manner.

157
00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:33.860
But in the small molecule space, what we know is small molecule

158
00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:34.950
inhibitors, when

159
00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:37.630
patients are treated with small molecules,

160
00:09:38.640 --> 00:09:42.389
end up generating resistance, 60% of which is driven by

161
00:09:42.420 --> 00:09:45.930
kinase domain mutations. And two of those mutations are

162
00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:49.600
really hotspots for creating resistance.

163
00:09:50.180 --> 00:09:53.940
Of course, the antibody shouldn't really care whether there is a resistant mutation

164
00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:54.419
or not.

165
00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:59.080
So we thought that perhaps these antibodies would also work

166
00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:01.260
in inhibitor-resistant settings.

167
00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:05.280
So those two mutations were created in

168
00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:09.600
both BAF3 cells and in the endogenous ICC line.

169
00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:13.180
And you can see from an internalization point of view, BD and BC

170
00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:17.109
still internalized just as well the two

171
00:10:17.109 --> 00:10:21.030
kinase-resistant mutations. And if you look at anti-proliferative activity,

172
00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:25.340
BC and BD have anti-proliferative activity for both of the

173
00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:27.680
intracellular kinase domain mutations.

174
00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:30.140
Again, working with Nabil Bardeesy,

175
00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:35.220
he took that 13-7 model, knocked in a

176
00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:38.720
kinase domain-resistant mutation, so now it's impervious to the effects

177
00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:41.800
of an FGFR2 inhibitor, yet antibody

178
00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:45.599
BC still has activity comparable to what it had in the

179
00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:49.400
original parental 13-7 model. So

180
00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:53.160
as predicted, the internalization is independent of whether you have a kinase

181
00:10:53.220 --> 00:10:56.920
domain mutation. And for me, this raises the interesting possibility that an

182
00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.760
antibody plus the small molecule might end up to be a way to

183
00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:03.740
defeat resistance in a combination strategy.

184
00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:09.100
So our model for how this works for FGFR2 is that unlike

185
00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:12.630
bivalent antibodies or improved over bivalent antibodies,

186
00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:16.980
biparotopic antibodies can cluster, drive internalization to the

187
00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.540
lysosome, and degrade the receptor, and inhibit tumor growth

188
00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:24.740
in the setting of an FGFR2 fusion.

189
00:11:26.340 --> 00:11:29.940
Okay, but this model also strongly suggests that these antibodies might be really

190
00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:31.880
good as antibody-drug conjugates.

191
00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:36.280
So we then went to take antibody BC

192
00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:40.520
and conjugate it to, let's say, pilot ADCs with

193
00:11:40.620 --> 00:11:42.280
MMAF, a non-cleavable

194
00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:45.140
monoauristatin

195
00:11:46.420 --> 00:11:50.180
payload, MMAE, which is cleavable, and diruxatukimod

196
00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:53.840
using a cleavable linker. And all three of these had

197
00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:55.280
activity in regressing

198
00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.480
tumors.Our interest is really in

199
00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:03.429
gastric cancer, where FGFR2 amplification is quite common in the 10% to

200
00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:07.520
20% range. And because deruxtecan-based payloads have

201
00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:11.360
already had significant activity in gastric cancer, we have focused

202
00:12:11.720 --> 00:12:15.600
both on comparing the deruxtecan payload to the MMAE

203
00:12:15.740 --> 00:12:18.580
payload in vivo ADC

204
00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:23.340
models, including breast, colon, and as I said, gastric cancer

205
00:12:23.420 --> 00:12:26.520
models. And in every case, we see significant

206
00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:30.080
regression of the tumors. In short, there are some

207
00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:33.740
differences. For example, this model responds to deruxtecan,

208
00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:37.560
while it does not respond to MMAE. This model has slightly

209
00:12:37.620 --> 00:12:40.880
better inhibitory activity with MMAE compared to

210
00:12:40.900 --> 00:12:44.720
deruxtecan. But in all five models, deruxtecan

211
00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:47.960
conjugated biparotopic antibody B and C have

212
00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.540
significant anti-tumor activity.

213
00:12:52.600 --> 00:12:56.460
So it's interesting to try to quantify the so-called bystander

214
00:12:56.500 --> 00:13:00.300
effect for these types of cleavable linkers and try to make

215
00:13:00.360 --> 00:13:03.820
sure it's true antigen-dependent bystander effect.

216
00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:07.080
So as an example, we create

217
00:13:07.300 --> 00:13:10.710
luciferase-containing FGFR2-negative cells,

218
00:13:11.300 --> 00:13:14.840
as well as some of the FGFR2-positive cells that I showed you.

219
00:13:15.220 --> 00:13:18.660
And then we can mix luciferase-positive cells, which have no

220
00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:22.180
FGFR2, with the luciferase-negative cells, which

221
00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:26.160
have FGFR2, in an admixed model.

222
00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:29.880
And I won't show you all of the different controls, but if we now

223
00:13:30.040 --> 00:13:33.520
take either PBS or the biparotopic BC

224
00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:34.300
ADC,

225
00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:39.440
in this case, MMAE, you can see in the presence of the admixed

226
00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:42.420
population, we can kill the

227
00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:44.780
FGFR2-negative cells. So

228
00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:47.020
I don't think this is a big surprise.

229
00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:51.060
You can see bystander effects, but we see robust killing of

230
00:13:51.160 --> 00:13:54.930
FGFR2-negative cells, and in data I'm not showing, with minimal

231
00:13:54.980 --> 00:13:58.820
effects on the FGFR2-negative cells when implanted by themselves.

232
00:14:01.100 --> 00:14:04.990
Okay, so that is our work on FGFR2, both some of which is

233
00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:05.899
published. The ADC

234
00:14:06.720 --> 00:14:10.540
work is not published. But we're interested in the general problem of

235
00:14:10.600 --> 00:14:13.960
how we can generate combinatorial biotherapeutics more

236
00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:17.990
effectively than starting with these 15 biparatopics we had, which is

237
00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.480
really sampling a very small diversity of possible

238
00:14:21.560 --> 00:14:25.420
epitope combinations. And one of the papers that really

239
00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:29.280
inspires this thinking, though we're not achieving anything like they did,

240
00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:32.280
is from Chugai, who developed a

241
00:14:33.180 --> 00:14:36.980
marketed antibody called HEMLIBRA, which is a replacement for factor

242
00:14:37.100 --> 00:14:40.870
VIII. And so what HEMLIBRA does is bring factor

243
00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:45.480
X and IX together in a way that replicates what factor

244
00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:49.430
VIII normally does. And I love this quote from their "Nature Medicine" paper,

245
00:14:49.870 --> 00:14:53.260
"To create this type of bispecific antibody, we screened

246
00:14:53.300 --> 00:14:57.020
approximately 40,000 of these antibodies by an

